  • The challenge for this project is to develop a deep learning GAN (Generative Adversarial Network) that learns from Monet art and can reproduce non Monet paintings in his signature style. The project will be scored on MiFID which is a quantitative evaluation metric where lower values mean a better model.
  • A GAN consists of two components, a generator which creates images to mimic Monet and a discriminator which can spot the difference between real Monet paintings and artificial ones. These two models are trained in opposition which in theory leads to progressively better results from the generator.
  • The data consists of 300 Monet paintings that are 256 pixels by 256 pixels. This is what the model will be trained on. A second directory contains 7028 images that are 256 pixels by 256 pixels that will be transformed into Monet style.

def display_images_from_directory(directory, title, num_images=5):
    images = os.listdir(directory)[:num_images]
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
    for i, img_name in enumerate(images):
        img_path = os.path.join(directory, img_name)
        img = Image.open(img_path)
        plt.subplot(1, num_images, i + 1)
        plt.imshow(img)
        plt.axis('off')
        plt.title(title)
    plt.show()

# Monet Paintings

# image properties
def check_image_properties(directory):
    file_count = 0
    image_shapes = []
    for file_name in os.listdir(directory):
        file_path = os.path.join(directory, file_name)
        try:
            img = Image.open(file_path)
            image_shapes.append(img.size)
            file_count += 1
        except Exception as e:
            print(f"Error reading file {file_name}: {e}")
    return file_count, set(image_shapes)

# Monet paintings
monet_count, monet_shapes = check_image_properties(monet_dir)

print(f"Photos: {photo_count} images, Dimensions: {photo_shapes}")

# Pixel intensity histogram
def plot_pixel_histogram(image_path, title):
    img = Image.open(image_path)
    img_array = np.array(img)
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
    for i, color in enumerate(['Red', 'Green', 'Blue']):
        plt.hist(img_array[..., i].flatten(), bins=50, alpha=0.5, label=f'{color} Channel', color=color.lower())
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel('Pixel Intensity')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

Model Architecture¶

For this model I will be utilizing latent vector as input and generate a 256 x 256 image. In theory the image should look progressively more and more like a Monet painting through upsampling. Each upsampling layer that occurs increases complexity and provides space for the model to apply its learned “Monetification”. Each upsampling layer cuts the number of filters to counter balance the added complexity of the upsampling. This helps with model building time, overfitting and memory usage.

  • Input Layer

    • Takes in a latent vector of a given size which serves as the seed to create new images

  • Dense Layer

    • Changes the latent vector into a multi dimensional array which can then be convolutionally processed
    • The output is 16 x 16
    • The activation (LeakyReLu) provides non-linearity

  • Upsampling Layers

    • Spatial dimensions double each layer until 256x256 is reached form 16x16
    • Filter number decreases

  • I will use random search for hyperparameter tuning to optimize model performance. The values tested will be:

    • Learning Rate: [0.00005, 0.0001, 0.00015, 0.0002, 0.00025, 0.0003, 0.00035, 0.0004, 0.00045, 0.0005]
    • Beta 1: [0.4, 0.5, 0.6, 0.7, 0.8, 0.9]
    • Latent Dimension: [50, 100, 150, 200, 250, 300]
    • Generator Filters: [64, 128, 256, 512]
    • Discriminator Filters: [64, 128, 256, 512]
    • Dropout Rate: [0.2, 0.3, 0.4, 0.5]

Model Building¶

In [7]:
def build_generator(latent_dim, filters):
    model = Sequential()
    
    # Input layer
    model.add(Input(shape=(latent_dim,)))
    
    # First Dense layer
    model.add(Dense(filters * 16 * 16))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.2))
    model.add(Reshape((16, 16, filters)))
    
    # Upsampling to 32x32
    model.add(Conv2DTranspose(filters // 2, kernel_size=4, strides=2, padding='same'))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.2))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    
    # Upsample to 64x64
    model.add(Conv2DTranspose(filters // 4, kernel_size=4, strides=2, padding='same'))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.2))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    
    # Upsample to 128x128
    model.add(Conv2DTranspose(filters // 8, kernel_size=4, strides=2, padding='same'))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.2))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    
    # Upsample to 256x256 and output layer
    model.add(Conv2DTranspose(3, kernel_size=4, strides=2, padding='same', activation='tanh'))
    
    return model

    "latent_dim": [50, 100, 150, 200, 250, 300],                 
    "gen_filters": [64, 128, 256, 512],                          
    "disc_filters": [64, 128, 256, 512],
    "dropout_rate": np.linspace(0.2, 0.5, 4).tolist(),           
}
In [9]:
def random_search(param_grid, num_trials=20):
    best_params = None
    best_loss = float('inf')
    for trial in range(num_trials):
        # Randomly sample hyperparameters
        params = {key: random.choice(values) for key, values in param_grid.items()}
        print(f"\nTrial {trial + 1}/{num_trials}: Testing parameters {params}")
        
        # Extract hyperparameters
        latent_dim = params["latent_dim"]
        gen_filters = params["gen_filters"]
        disc_filters = params["disc_filters"]
        dropout_rate = params["dropout_rate"]
        learning_rate = params["learning_rate"]
        beta_1 = params["beta_1"]
        
        # Build models with these values
        generator = build_generator(latent_dim, gen_filters)
        discriminator = build_discriminator(disc_filters, dropout_rate)
        
        # Compile discriminator
        discriminator.compile(
            loss='binary_crossentropy',
            optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate, beta_1=beta_1)
        )
        
        # Build GAN
        discriminator.trainable = False
        gan_input = Input(shape=(latent_dim,))
        gan_output = discriminator(generator(gan_input))
        gan = Model(gan_input, gan_output)
        gan.compile(
            loss='binary_crossentropy',
            optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate, beta_1=beta_1)
        )
        
        # Evaluate 
        noise = np.random.normal(0, 1, (10, latent_dim))
        labels = np.ones((10, 1))
        loss = gan.evaluate(noise, labels, verbose=0)
        
        print(f"Loss: {loss:.4f}")
        
        # Update best parameters if current loss is lower
        if loss < best_loss:
            best_loss = loss
            best_params = params
    
    print(f"\nBest parameters: {best_params}, Best loss: {best_loss:.4f}")
    return best_params
In [10]:
def build_discriminator(filters, dropout_rate, input_shape=(256, 256, 3)):
    model = Sequential()
    
    # Input layer
    model.add(Input(shape=input_shape))
    
    # First Conv layer
    model.add(Conv2D(filters, kernel_size=4, strides=2, padding='same'))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.2))
    
    # Second Conv layer
    model.add(Conv2D(filters * 2, kernel_size=4, strides=2, padding='same'))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.2))
    model.add(Dropout(dropout_rate))
    
    # Third Conv layer
    model.add(Conv2D(filters * 4, kernel_size=4, strides=2, padding='same'))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.2))
    model.add(Dropout(dropout_rate))
    
    # Flatten and output layer
    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
    
    return model

def load_data():
    monet_dir = '/kaggle/input/gan-getting-started/monet_jpg/'
    monet_images = []
    # Convert all photos to 256x256
    for img_name in os.listdir(monet_dir):
        img_path = os.path.join(monet_dir, img_name)
        img = Image.open(img_path).convert('RGB').resize((256, 256))
        img_array = np.array(img)
        if img_array.shape == (256, 256, 3):
            monet_images.append(img_array)
    monet_images = np.array(monet_images, dtype='float32')
    return monet_images

# Load Monet images
real_images = load_data()
print(f"Loaded {real_images.shape[0]} real images.")

# Normalize images to range [-1, 1]
real_images = (real_images - 127.5) / 127.5

# Set GAN output to generators output

# Build the GAN model by combining the generator and discriminator
gan = Model(gan_input, gan_output)

# Compile GAN model

    loss='binary_crossentropy',                       
    optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate,       
                   beta_1=beta_1)                     
)

# Function to save and plot photos as model is being applied to them
def save_generated_images(epoch, generator, latent_dim, examples=5):
    noise = np.random.normal(0, 1, (examples, latent_dim))
    gen_imgs = generator.predict(noise)
    gen_imgs = 0.5 * gen_imgs + 0.5
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, examples, figsize=(15, 3))
    for i in range(examples):
        axs[i].imshow(gen_imgs[i])
        axs[i].axis('off')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig(f"generated_images_epoch_{epoch}.png")
    plt.close()
In [ ]:
def train_gan(epochs, batch_size, save_interval):
    # Loop over the number of epochs training both generator and discriminator models
    for epoch in range(1, epochs + 1):
      
        # Train Discriminator Section
    
        # Get random real images
        idx = np.random.randint(0, real_images.shape[0], batch_size)
        real_imgs = real_images[idx]  
        real_labels = np.ones((batch_size, 1))  
        
        # Generate fake images
        noise = np.random.normal(0, 1, (batch_size, latent_dim))  
        fake_imgs = generator.predict(noise)  
        fake_labels = np.zeros((batch_size, 1))  
        
        # Combine real and fake images and labels
        combined_imgs = np.concatenate([real_imgs, fake_imgs])  
        combined_labels = np.concatenate([real_labels, fake_labels])  
        
        # Shuffle 
        shuffle_idx = np.random.permutation(len(combined_imgs))  
        combined_imgs = combined_imgs[shuffle_idx]  
        combined_labels = combined_labels[shuffle_idx]  
        
        # Train the discriminator on the combined data
        d_loss = discriminator.train_on_batch(combined_imgs, combined_labels)
        
      
        #  Train Generator Section 
       
        # Create new noise input
        noise = np.random.normal(0, 1, (batch_size, latent_dim))  
        
        # Labels for the generator training
        valid_labels = np.ones((batch_size, 1))  
        
        # Train the generator via the GAN model
        g_loss = gan.train_on_batch(noise, valid_labels)
        
        # Progress
        if epoch % 10 == 0:
            print(f"Epoch {epoch} [D loss: {d_loss:.4f}] [G loss: {g_loss:.4f}]")
        
        # Save images
        if epoch % save_interval == 0:
            save_generated_images(epoch, generator, latent_dim)

# Function to gemerate amd save photos to kaggle directory 
def generate_and_save_images(generator, latent_dim, total_images, zip_filename='images.zip'):
    zip_path = os.path.join('/kaggle/working/', zip_filename)
    try:
        with zipfile.ZipFile(zip_path, 'w') as zipf:
            for i in range(total_images):
                # Create random noise vector
                noise = np.random.normal(0, 1, (1, latent_dim))
                # Create image
                gen_img = generator.predict(noise)
                # Rescale pixel values 
                gen_img = 127.5 * gen_img + 127.5
                gen_img = gen_img.astype('uint8')
                # Remove the batch dimension
                gen_img = gen_img[0]
                # Convert to PIL Image
                img = Image.fromarray(gen_img)
                # Save image to an in-memory buffer
                img_buffer = io.BytesIO()
                img.save(img_buffer, format='JPEG')
                img_buffer.seek(0)
                # Write image to zip file
                img_name = f"{i}.jpg"
                zipf.writestr(img_name, img_buffer.read())
    except Exception as error:
        print(f"An error occurred: {error}")

Results¶

  • My project went reasonably well. It was probably my least favorite out of the projects for this course because there was no testing set to view model performance. Determining how good your output required submitting to Kaggle, which took a very long time. I ended up in the top 100 on the leaderboard with a score of 460 which is better than the required 1000 score. But my end result of images was awful. Since we were advised not to optimize this I will keep these results but they arent very good.

  • The results of my hyperameter tuning were:

    • learning_rate: 0.0001,
    • beta_1: 0.7,
    • latent_dim: 250,
    • gen_filters: 128,
    • disc_filters: 128,
    • dropout_rate: 0.4

  • My learning rate of .0001 is pretty low but its not the highest or lowest value I tested, which suggests to me that its near the optimal value. For my beta of 0.7 it’s a change from 0.9 which is the default for GAN from my research. This lower value suggests that responsiveness was more important than momentum. The latent dimension value of 250 leads to faster image generation at the tradeoff of less complexity. Generator filters being a smaller value of 128 results in a more simple generator that is faster at training and generation at the tradeoff of complexity. The same result for discriminator filters leads to a simple model that is fast but could struggle more when trying to determine which images are fake vs real. A dropout rate of 0.4 is pretty standard average value. I think my placement on the leaderboard is a result of a too simple model. My plan was to counteract my simple model with more epochs but was unable to run more then 250 in the competition due to time constraints.

  • To display some results here are some images that have had Monet's style applied to them. The usual outline for this week is gone so I am not sure what the professor wants if anything...

# Show modified photos 
def display_images(zip_file_path, title="Images from ZIP", num_images=5):
    with zipfile.ZipFile(zip_file_path, 'r') as zipf:
        file_list = zipf.namelist()[:num_images]  
        plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
        for i, file_name in enumerate(file_list):
            try:
                with zipf.open(file_name) as file:
                    img = Image.open(file)
                    plt.subplot(1, num_images, i + 1)
                    plt.imshow(img)
                    plt.axis('off')
                    plt.title(f"{title} {i + 1}")
            except Exception as e:
                print(f"Error loading image {file_name}: {e}")
        plt.show()
